          "body": "The hymn reaches its climax with two pairs of images. First: the pillars of heaven tremble and are amazed at God's rebuke. The rebuke is a spoken word — God's voice, not a physical force — and the structural supports of the cosmos respond with trembling. Second, and most theologically dense: God quieted the sea by His power, shattered Rahab by His understanding, cleared the skies by His breath, and pierced the fleeing serpent by His hand. Rahab and the fleeing serpent (nachash bariach) are drawn from the chaos-monster mythology of the ancient Near East — Tiamat in Babylon, Yamm in Canaan, the primordial forces of disorder that cosmogonic myths presented as God's great opponents. Job does not concede their autonomy. He demythologizes them entirely: they are creatures already defeated. God did not merely overcome them; He shattered them. The tense is past and completed. This matters enormously in Job's situation: the chaos that has invaded his life is not an autonomous power beyond God's control. Every chaos-power is already a pierced and fleeing enemy of the God Job is addressing. Spurgeon noted on similar texts that the Christian's comfort in suffering is not that God will eventually defeat evil but that He already has."
