          "title": "The epistemology of the fringe (26:14)",
          "body": "The entire cosmic panorama — underworld, earth, sky, sea, heavens, chaos-monsters — is gathered up in a single statement of radical humility: 'Behold, these are the fringes of His ways.' Qatsah is the outermost edge, the margin, the periphery. What Job has just described is not the whole of God but His sleeve. The whisper (shemets — used only here in the Hebrew Bible, the rarest possible word for minimal sound) we hear of Him is not the full message. The thunder of His power — gevurah — is beyond comprehension. This is the chapter's hermeneutical key and also the book's. The friends have been operating as though they possess an adequate theology of divine retribution that explains Job's situation. Job is insisting that an adequate theology of God is, by definition, impossible — not because God is unknowable but because He is infinite. John Owen, in his treatise on the mortification of sin, observed that the soul that has lost its sense of God's greatness will always reduce suffering to a simple equation. Job 26:14 refuses that reduction. The thunder remains beyond understanding. And yet — crucially — Job does not despair. He marvels. The incomprehensibility of God is not a threat to Job; it is, in the deepest sense, his only hope: the God who is beyond fringes is also the God who holds the earth on nothing and has already shattered Rahab."
