        "number": 2,
        "title": "The underworld is naked — God sees what is most hidden",
        "range": "26:5–6",
        "excerpt": "Naked is Sheol before Him, and Abaddon has no covering.",
        "body": "The doxology begins at the lowest possible point in the ancient cosmological imagination: beneath the earth, beneath the cosmic waters, in the place of the dead. The Rephaim tremble (26:5). Sheol is naked, Abaddon uncovered (26:6). The movement from Bildad's pretension to this affirmation is not accidental — the God Bildad was reducing to a theological system is the God before whom even death has no secrets.\n\nThe paired images of nakedness and absence of covering carry Levitical resonance. To be naked and uncovered is to be completely exposed, without defense or concealment. In the ancient Near East, the underworld was conceived as the realm of permanent hiddenness — the place you went where the gods could not see you (cf. Psalm 139:8, where David makes the same counter-claim: 'If I make my bed in Sheol, behold, You are there'). Job strips the underworld of that concealment. The stative verbs are key: Sheol does not become naked at some future judgment; it IS naked, perpetually, before God's gaze.\n\nFor the book of Job, this has direct pastoral force. Job has cried repeatedly that God seems to have turned His face away, that his suffering happens in divine silence. The doxology of 26:5–6 is Job's own counter-testimony: the God who sees through Sheol certainly sees Job. The problem is not divine blindness but divine mystery — a very different problem. As Tim Keller observed, the friends offered Job a God small enough to be explained; Job insists on the God who is too large to be escaped even in death.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rephaim* (26:5, 'departed spirits') are the shades of the dead — the word may connect to *rapha'* (to be weak, powerless) or to the Rephaim of Canaanite mythology, heroic dead warriors. Either way, these are the most powerful human dead, and even they tremble. *Avaddon* (26:6) derives from *'abad* (to perish, to be destroyed) and appears six times in the wisdom literature (Job 26:6; 28:22; 31:12; Psalm 88:11; Proverbs 15:11; 27:20). In Revelation 9:11 it becomes the name of the angel of the abyss. The New Testament's use of the same term confirms the canonical continuity of the underworld imagery."
